# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: donie-bush
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] The **1900 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office on June 1, 1900, determined the resident population of the United States to be 76,212,168, an increase of 21.01% from the 62,979,766 persons enumerated during the 1890 census.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] It was the last census to be conducted before the founding of the permanent United States Census Bureau.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] The census saw the nation's largest city, New York City, more than double in size due to the consolidation with Brooklyn, becoming in the process the first U.S. city to record a population growth of over three million — Brooklyn was previously the 4th largest city in the United States on its own.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] Oversight of the statistics was by Frederick Howard Wines and Walter F.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1900 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] Statistician Frederick Ludwig Hoffman criticized the conduct of the census.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, and digital indices.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1900 census are freely available through IPUMS.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:donie-bush/1900-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1900, on a map of the modern United States.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The **1908 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1908.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 8, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] In a rematch of the prior year's postseason, the postseason began with Game 1 of the fifth modern World Series on October 10 and ended with Game 5 on October 14.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to one, capturing their second championship in franchise history, and the first team to win back-to-back World Series.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Americans renamed as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The 1908 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 with all but the Pittsburgh Pirates and St.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 8.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 10 and October 14.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games (10 in AL, 6 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 10 and ended on October 14 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1908 World Series in five games.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:donie-bush/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics would play their final game at Columbia Park with a doubleheader on October 3 against the Boston Red Sox, moving into Shibe Park for the start of the 1909 season.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The **1908 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1908 season.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The fifth edition of the World Series, it matched the defending National League (NL) champion Chicago Cubs against the American League (AL) champion Detroit Tigers in a rematch of the 1907 Series.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] In this first-ever rematch of this young event, the Cubs won in five games for their second straight World Series title.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The 1908 World Series was significant for being the last World Series championship the Cubs would win until 2016 (108 years later).
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] That became the longest World Series championship drought for any team in North American sports history.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The Cubs had been one of baseball's most dominant teams in the early 1900s.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] This was the year of the infamous "Merkle's Boner" play that allowed the Chicago Cubs to reach the World Series after beating the New York Giants (now the San Francisco Giants) in a one-game "playoff", actually the makeup game for the tie that the Merkle play had caused.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The Series was anticlimactic after tight pennant races in both leagues.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Ty Cobb had a much better World Series than in the previous year, as did the rest of his team.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The final two games, held in Detroit, were shutouts.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] This was also the most poorly attended World Series in history, with the final game drawing a record-low 6,210 fans.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Attendance in Chicago was harmed by a ticket-scalping scheme that fans accused the club's owner of participating in, and the World Series was boycotted to some degree.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] For the first time, four umpires were used in the series, in alternating two-man teams.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Games 1, 4, and 5 were played in Detroit, while Games 2 and 3 were played in Chicago.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Had the series continued, Game 6 would have been played in Chicago, and the home team for Game 7 would have been decided randomly, "by lot".
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] This was also the first World Series with a defending champion and the first to feature a team that won back-to-back titles.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] After a bunt groundout, Harry Steinfeldt's RBI single put Chicago up 2–1.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] After a walk, Ed Summers relieved Killian and allowed an RBI groundout to Joe Tinker and Johnny Kling reached on an error that allowed another run to score.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The Cubs added another run in the seventh on Steinfedlt's sacrifice fly.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, with runners on second and third, Boss Schmidt's groundout, Red Downs's ground-rule double, and Summers's single scored a run each.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Next inning, Claude Rossman's two-run single off of Mordecai Brown put the Tigers up 6–5.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] In the top of the ninth, three straight one-out singles loaded the bases before Solly Hofman's single scored two and Joe Tinker's bunt single scored another.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] After a double steal, Johnny Kling's two-run single put the Cubs up 10–6.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Brown pitched a scoreless bottom of the ninth despite allowing a single and walk as the Cubs went up 1–0 in the series.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] A scoreless tie in the bottom of the eighth came to an end when Joe Tinker's two-run homer launched a six-run Cub outburst.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Tinker's blast was the first World Series home run since Patsy Dougherty in 1903.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] After a ground-rule double and groundout, RBI singles by Jimmy Sheckard and Johnny Evers and an RBI triple by Frank Schulte (the last two hits coming off after stolen bases) scored a run each.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] A wild pitch to Frank Chance scored the Cubs' last run.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The Tigers avoided a shutout in the ninth when Davy Jones drew a leadoff walk, moved to second on a groundout and scored on Ty Cobb's single.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Orval Overall's complete-game win took just 90 minutes.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] It was in this game that Ty Cobb enjoyed the finest World Series outing he ever had.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The 21-year-old Georgian rapped three singles and a double in five at-bats, and stole two bases.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] In the top of the ninth, he singled and promptly stole second and third, but then the hyped-up boy wonder pressed his luck and was thrown out trying to steal home.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] This was the only Tiger win in their back-to-back first two World Series losses to the Cubs.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Detroit struck first in the top of the first when Charley O'Leary hit a one-out single, moved to second on a groundout and scored on Ty Cobb's single.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The Cubs responded in the fourth on Frank Chance's RBI single.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] After stealing second, an error on Harry Steinfeldt's ground ball and Solly Hofman's triple scored a run each.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] In the top of the sixth, after a single and walk, singles by Sam Crawford, Ty Cobb, and Claude Rossman scored a run each.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] After a double play, Ira Thomas's RBI double made it 6–3 Tigers.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] They added two more runs in the eighth on Bill Coughlin's bases loaded sacrifice fly followed by George Mullin's RBI single.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] This one was over in 1 hour and 35 minutes.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] RBI singles by Harry Steinfeldt and Solly Hofman in the third inning after two walks gave Mordecai Brown all the support he'd need.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Brown allowed only four hits and walked none.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The Cubs added another run in the ninth when Frank Chance reached on an error with two on.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] In the first inning, Overall registered four strikeouts, as Claude Rossman reached on an uncaught third strike.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] This was the first, and to date only, instance of a four-strikeout inning in a World Series game.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Overall allowed only three hits, walking four and striking out 10 for his second win of the series.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] In 18+1⁄3 innings pitched during the series, he allowed only seven hits and two runs for an ERA of 0.98.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The Cubs scored the game's first run in the first on three straight one-out singles, the last of which to Frank Chance scoring a run, then added another run in the fifth on Johnny Evers's double after two walks.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] Boss Schmidt, who made the last out of the 1907 Series with a popup to short, also made the last out of this Series with a feeble catcher-to-first groundout.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] This was also the first World Series game in which neither team committed an error.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The Cubs did not win another World Series title until finally reclaiming the crown in 2016, a drought of 108 years, which remains the longest in MLB history.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The attendance during this final game of the series, 6,210, was the smallest crowd in World Series history.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] It also remains the fastest postseason game in major-league history, at 1 hour 25 minutes.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] This was the Cubs’ last championship until 2016, 108 years later, when they finally ended their century-long championship drought over the Cleveland Indians in seven games.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The Cubs would lose in their next seven World Series prior to their 2016 championship season.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] This was the second straight World Series defeat for the Tigers.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] They would return to the Fall Classic the next year, but were defeated by the Pittsburgh Pirates in seven games.
[src:donie-bush/1908-world-series] The Tigers and Cubs would meet again in 1935 and 1945, and in those series the Tigers returned the favor, winning in six and seven games respectively.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The **1909 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1909 season.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The sixth edition of the World Series, it featured the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates against the American League (AL) champion Detroit Tigers.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The Pirates won the Series in seven games to capture their first championship of the modern Major League Baseball era and the second championship in the club's history.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Pittsburgh-based team.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] This Series is best remembered for featuring two of the very best players of the time, Pittsburgh shortstop Honus Wagner, and Detroit outfielder Ty Cobb.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Sites: games 1, 2 in Pittsburgh; games 3, 4 in Detroit; game 5 in Pittsburgh; games 6, 7 in Detroit.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The Pirates had won the National League pennant in 1909 behind the brilliant play of Honus Wagner, who led the league with a .339 batting average and 100 runs batted in.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Detroit returned for their third consecutive Fall Classic, determined to erase the memories of their previous efforts.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The Tigers were also backed up by the heavy bat of Ty Cobb (who had just won his third consecutive American League batting title) and a formidable pitching staff.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] They might have finally won the Series in their third try, had it not been for Pirates rookie Babe Adams.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Manager Fred Clarke started him, on a hunch, in Game 1.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Adams won that game and two more, setting a World Series record for rookies.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The Tigers thus became the first AL team to win three consecutive pennants and the first team to lose three straight World Series (the New York Giants would lose three straight Series from 1911 to 1913).
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The Pirates ran at will against the weak Detroit catching corps, stealing 18 bases in seven games.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] For the first time, four umpires were used at the same time, with the standard plate umpire and base umpire along with two outfield umpires.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] On June 14, 2009, the series' 100th anniversary was celebrated, when the Tigers and Pirates played each other in Pittsburgh.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Both teams wore throwback uniforms similar to those worn in 1909.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The stadium's public address and sound systems were also turned off, simulating the game conditions in 1909.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Ty Cobb had a fairly quiet Series, going 6-for-26 with two stolen bases and one caught stealing.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] There is a long-standing legend that Cobb, standing on first base, called the German-ancestored Honus Wagner a "krauthead", told him he was going to steal second, and was not only thrown out but that Wagner tagged him in the mouth, ball in hand, drawing blood from Cobb's lip.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] However, an examination of the play-by-play does not indicate that such a play occurred.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] In the one "caught stealing" charged to Cobb, during the first inning of Game 4, he was actually safe at second due to a throwing error by first baseman Bill Abstein.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] This story is largely attributed to the creative press at the time, and Wagner and Cobb were actually on good terms.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Rookie Babe Adams, who had compiled a 12–3 record during the regular season, unexpectedly drew the start for Game 1.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] He responded with a six-hit, 4–1 victory sparked by Clarke's game-tying home run in the bottom of the fourth inning.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The Tigers began their 7–2 comeback win (after a two-run Pirate bottom of the first) with three runs in the top of the third, tying the Series at one game apiece.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Honus Wagner had three hits, three RBI and three stolen bases as the Pirates regained the lead in the Series, two games to one.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The win-swapping continued with Detroit taking Game 4.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Tiger ace George Mullin threw a five-hit shutout while striking out 10 Pirates, again evening the Series at two games apiece.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Babe Adams threw another six-hitter, for an 8–4 triumph and a 3–2 Series lead for his Pirates.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Mullin, after being roughed up for three first-inning runs, surrendered only one more and wound up with the win, knotting the Series at three games apiece.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] With the Series coming down to a climactic seventh game (the first to go the distance), Pittsburgh's Fred Clarke went with two-game winner Babe Adams as his pitcher, while Detroit Manager Hugh Jennings decided on Bill Donovan, a complete-game winner in Game 2.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] He hit the first Pirate batter and went on to walk six in the first two innings.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] He was pulled after three with Adams confidently holding a 2–0 lead.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Pittsburgh never looked back, as Babe nailed his third six-hitter and third win of the Series for an 8–0 championship victory.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Honus Wagner continued to prove his Cooperstown worthiness by hitting .333, with seven RBI and six stolen bases (the latter total standing as a Series record until Lou Brock surpassed it in 1967).
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] On the other side, Ty Cobb did not fare as well.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Appearing in what would be his last Series (although he would remain active through 1928), Cobb batted only .231 although he did lead the Tigers, losers of their third Series in three years, with six RBI.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] It was the first time that one team won the odd-numbered games; the other, the even; it did not happen again until 1962.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The championship was recorded by Essanay Co., and sold double the expected number of copies.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] Kennedy speculated that the film would set a world record for sales.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] No two professional sports teams from Detroit and Pittsburgh would play for a major professional sports championship again until the 2008 Stanley Cup Final between the Detroit Red Wings and Pittsburgh Penguins.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The Pirates would return to the World Series in 1925, where they overcame a 3–1 series deficit and defeated the Washington Senators in seven games.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] This was the third straight Would Series loss for the Tigers.
[src:donie-bush/1909-world-series] The Tigers would not play in another Fall Classic for 25 years, where they lost yet again in seven games, this time to the St.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The **1921 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1921.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 2, with the New York Giants and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 18th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 8 on October 13.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] In the first Subway Series World Series, the Giants defeated the Yankees, five games to three, capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1905.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Cleveland Indians from the 1920 season.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] 1921 was the first of three straight seasons in which the Yankees would lead the majors in wins.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Babe Ruth broke the single season home run record for the third consecutive season by hitting 59 home runs in 152 games.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Ruth also broke Roger Connor's record for the most home runs all time when he hit his 139th home run on July 18 against Bert Cole.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The record for career strikeouts, previously held by Cy Young was also broken in 1921 by Walter Johnson; Johnson led the league in strikeouts with 143 and ended the season with 2,835 strikeouts.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Young struck out 2,803 during his career.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds set a Major League record for the fewest strikeouts in a season, with only 308.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Future Hall of Famers Kiki Cuyler and Goose Goslin both debuted in September 1921.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The 1921 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 13 with all but the Chicago White Sox and Detroit Tigers playing.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 2.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 13.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] 3 tie games (2 in AL, 1 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics had two tie games.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Tigers and Washington Senators had one tie game each.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 13 with the New York Giants defeating the New York Yankees in the 1921 World Series in eight games.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] On August 5, the Pittsburgh Pirates 8–5 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies at Forbes Field was the first Major League game to be broadcast on radio.
[src:donie-bush/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Harold Arlin calls the game for Pittsburgh station KDKA.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The **1923 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1923.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 7, with the New York Giants and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 20th World Series on October 10 and ended with Game 6 on October 15.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] In the third consecutive iteration of the Subway Series, the Yankees defeated the Giants, four games to two, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] This was the third World Series between the two teams, and the first to see the Yankees win over the Giants.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Giants from the 1922 season.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second of eight seasons that "League Awards", a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), were issued.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] Only an American League award was given in 1923.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The 1923 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 17 with all teams playing, while American League Opening Day took place the following day with all teams playing.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 7.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 10 and October 15.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] 7 tie games (5 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 10 and ended on October 15 with the New York Yankees defeating the New York Giants in the 1923 World Series in six games.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Yankees leave the Polo Grounds, where they shared with the New York Giants for the previous 10 seasons, and open Yankee Stadium, where they would play for 84 seasons through 1973 and 1976 through 2008.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The Yankees, whose home had been Manhattan for their entire existence, moved into the Bronx where they remain to this day.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] Referring to the Philadelphia Phillies' home at National League Park, on July 11, *The Philadelphia Inquirer* coined the term Baker Bowl.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] "Baker Bowl" became a common name for the stadium until its closure in 1938, although the Phillies would still refer to the venue as its official "National League Park" name in newspaper advertisements.
[src:donie-bush/1923-major-league-baseball-season] On August 21, Clark Griffith, owner of the Washington Senators since 1920, announced that National Park would be named after himself, Griffith Stadium.
[src:donie-bush/1923-washington-senators-season] The **1923 Washington Senators** won 75 games, lost 78, and finished in fourth place in the American League.
[src:donie-bush/1923-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Donie Bush and played home games at Griffith Stadium.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush was the starting shortstop for the Detroit Tigers from 1908 to 1921 and an infielder for the Washington Senators from 1921 to 1923.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He was recognized as one of the best defensive shortstops of the dead-ball era.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He had more putouts, assists, and total chances than any other shortstop of the era, and his 1914 totals of 425 putouts and 969 chances are still American League records for shortstops (and the major league record for putouts).
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He also led the American League in assists by a shortstop on five occasions and holds the major league record with nine triple plays.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] As a batter, Bush did not hit for a high batting average but was regularly among the major league leaders in drawing bases on balls, sacrifice hits, stolen bases, and runs scored.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] At the time of his retirement in 1923, Bush's 1,158 bases on balls ranked second in major league history.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His 337 sacrifice hits still ranks fifth in major league history, and his 1909 total of 52 sacrifice hits is the fourth highest in major league history.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He ranked among the American League leaders in stolen bases ten times, and, during the decade from 1910 to 1919, the only players to score more runs than Bush were Ty Cobb, Eddie Collins, and Tris Speaker.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush's 400 stolen bases as a Tiger rank second in franchise history, behind only Cobb.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His 1927 Pittsburgh Pirates won the National League pennant and lost to the 1927 Yankees in the World Series.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He was given the title "King of Baseball" during Major League Baseball's 1963 winter meetings.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Baseball" in Indianapolis and was an inaugural inductee of the Indiana Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush was born in 1887 in Indianapolis, Indiana.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He was the son of Irish-American parents and raised on the east side of Indianapolis.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His father died when Bush was a child, and at the time of the 1900 United States census, Bush was living with his mother and two older siblings in Center Township, near or in Indianapolis.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush was one of the best defensive shortstops of the dead-ball era.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He collected more putouts, assists, and total chances than any other shortstop of the era, and his 1914 total of 425 putouts is still the Major League record for shortstops.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His 1914 total of 969 chances is also still the American League record.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush also holds the Major League record (shared with Bid McPhee and John Morrill) for most career triple plays with nine.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] As a batter, Bush ranked among the American League leaders in bases on balls 12 straight years, from 1909 through 1920, and led the league five times.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His career high was 118 bases on balls in 1915.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] During the decade from 1910 to 1919, no Major League player had more bases on balls than Bush.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] At the time of his retirement in 1923, Bush had 1,158 walks, second best in Major League history trailing only Eddie Collins.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush also collected 337 sacrifice hits in his career, ranking him fifth on the all-time Major League leader list (behind Hall of Famers Eddie Collins and Willie Keeler).
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He led the league with 52 sacrifice hits in 1909 (fourth highest single season total in Major League history) and hit another 48 (seventh highest single season total in Major League history) in 1920.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush was also one of the shortest players in the Major Leagues at five feet, six inches (1.7 meters) and weighed between 130 and 140 pounds.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush once said, "I used to tell 'em it ain't how big you are, it's how good you are.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] But whenever another team had an uncommonly small player, I'd slip up and compare heights.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush's nickname, "Donie", was reportedly bestowed on him as a result of a comment by Detroit teammate Ed Killian in 1909.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush explained, "One day after I had struck out, I asked Eddie Killian what kind of ball I swung at and missed.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush began his professional baseball career in 1905 playing for the Sault Ste.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Marie Soos in the Copper Country Soo League.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1906, he played portions of the season for the Zanesville Moguls in the Ohio–Pennsylvania League and the Saginaw Wa-was of the Southern Michigan League.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In early August 1906, he was acquired by the Dayton Veterans of the Central League.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He appeared in 58 games for Dayton, compiling a .158 batting average with 98 putouts and 156 assists.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1907, he played for the South Bend Greens in the Central League.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He appeared in 127 games, compiling a .279 batting average with nine doubles and seven triples.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] At the end of the 1907 season, after a good showing in South Bend, Bush was drafted by the Chicago White Sox, Boston Red Sox and Detroit Tigers, and was awarded to the Tigers.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He was sold by the Detroit team to play the 1908 season for the Indianapolis Browns of the American Association.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He appeared in 153 games for Indianapolis and was the team's starting shortstop with 330 putouts, 472 assists, 54 errors, 856 total chances, and a .937 fielding percentage.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] As a batter, he had 28 stolen bases, 18 sacrifice hits, seven triples, and a .247 batting average.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He helped Indianapolis win the American Association pennant for 1908, and at the end of the 1908 season, *The Sporting Life* wrote that Bush was "generally credited with being the best ball player outside the big leagues during the season in the minors which has just closed.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In late August 1908, Bush, then known as "Ownie", was sold by the Indianapolis club to the Detroit Tigers.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He joined the Tigers in mid-September after Detroit's starting shortstop, Charley O'Leary, had been injured.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush replaced O'Leary at shortstop for the team's final 20 regular season games.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush's performance in the final weeks of the season, during a tight pennant race, was credited with having "thrust the panting Tigers first over the line." Because Bush had not been with the Tigers for more than 30 days, he was ineligible to play in the 1908 World Series.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In January 1909, Bush signed a contract to return to the Tigers, and he became the Tigers' starting shortstop for the next 13 seasons.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He compiled a .273 batting average and a .380 on-base percentage in 1909 and led the American League with 676 plate appearances, 88 bases on balls, and 52 sacrifice hits.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His 52 sacrifice hits remains the fourth highest single season total in major league history, and his .380 on-base percentage was the third highest in the American League in 1909 behind teammate Ty Cobb and Eddie Collins.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His 114 runs scored was second in the league behind only Cobb.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush's 52 stolen bases also set an American League rookie record that stood for 83 years until Kenny Lofton stole 66 bases in 1992.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush also played in all seven games of the 1909 World Series against the Pittsburgh Pirates, becoming the surprise hitting star for Detroit.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] With Detroit stars Ty Cobb and Sam Crawford slumping in the World Series (batting .231 and .250 respectively), Bush hit .318 with an on-base percentage of .483.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He also scored five runs, collected five bases on balls, was twice hit by a pitch, and compiled nine putouts, 18 assists, and three double plays (but also committed five errors).
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] After a brief holdout in the spring of 1910, Bush re-signed with the Tigers in mid-March.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] During the 1910 and 1911 seasons, Bush led the American League in bases on balls for the second and third consecutive seasons.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His total of 49 stolen bases ranked third in the American League in 1910, and his 126 runs scored in 1911 ranked second in the league.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Defensively, Bush's 1910 fielding percentage of .940 led American League shortstops, and his 1910 defensive Wins Above Replacement (WAR) rating of 2.0 ranked third among all American League players, regardless of position.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1911, he led the American League's shortstops with 372 putouts, 556 assists, and 75 errors.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His range factor of 6.19 in 1911 was a career-high and the second best among American League shortstops.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In the voting for the 1911 Chalmers Award (the predecessor of the American League Most Valuable Player award), Bush finished in 14th place, as teammate Ty Cobb won the award.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1912, Bush led the major leagues with 117 bases on balls.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] *The Sporting Life* noted: "Bush is one of the hardest men in the game to pitch to.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He also ranked among the American League leaders with a defensive WAR of 1.8 (4th among players at all positions), 107 runs scored (7th), 37 stolen bases (8th), 317 putouts at shortstop (4th), a .929 fielding percentage (2nd among shortstops), and 66 errors (2nd).
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1913, Bush led the American League with 694 plate appearances and was again among the league leaders with 80 bases on balls (3rd), 44 stolen bases (6th), 98 runs (8th), 331 putouts at shortstop (2nd), and 510 assists at shortstop (2nd).
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] *Baseball Magazine* praised Bush for his range: "In the field Bush sometimes appears ragged, but this is not owing to lack of finish in handling stinging grounders.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] It is rather a direct result of his eagerness to spear everything within reach and just a little beyond.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1914, Bush led the American League with 721 plate appearances and 112 bases on balls while also scoring 97 runs and compiling 35 stolen bases and a .373 on-base percentage.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In the voting for the 1914 Chalmers Award (the predecessor of the American League Most Valuable Player award), Bush finished in a tie with Home Run Baker for third place, trailing only Eddie Collins and Sam Crawford, and ahead of Shoeless Joe Jackson, Tris Speaker and Ty Cobb.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1915, Bush, along with Detroit's all-star outfield of Ty Cobb, Sam Crawford, and Bobby Veach, helped lead the Tigers to a 100–54 record and a second-place finish in the American League.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Kofoed in *Baseball Magazine* rated Bush as the best shortstop in the American League.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Kofoed wrote that Bush had only five fewer chances than Rabbit Maranville and seven fewer errors, noted that Bush made "spectacular plays" in the field "day after day".
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Kofoed also dismissed those who relegated Bush to the "poor hitting class", noting that Bush got on base and scored more often than any of his Detroit teammates.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In appreciation of Bush's efforts during the 1915 season, Detroit fans raised funds to allow Bush to purchase a new Paige automobile.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1916, Bush continued to rank among the American League leaders in multiple categories with 75 bases on balls (7th), 27 sacrifice hits (9th), 435 assists (5th among all players regardless of position), 278 putouts at shortstop (4th), and a .954 fielding percentage at shortstop (3rd).
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] *Baseball Magazine*, in choosing its All Star American League Team, chose Bush at the shortstop position.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Lane observed: "But the best performer, taking everything into consideration, was Donie Bush of Detroit.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1917, Bush led the American League with 112 runs scored, stole 34 bases, and compiled a career-high batting average of .281 with a .370 on-base percentage.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush also broke up a noteworthy no-hitter on July 11, 1917.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] With Boston Red Sox pitcher Babe Ruth having allowed no hits, Bush hit a scratch single in the eighth inning.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] After giving up the single to Bush, Ruth struck out the Tigers' Bobby Veach, Sam Crawford, and Ty Cobb in the ninth inning to secure a 1–0 complete game shutout.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In a 1942 speech in Los Angeles‚ Ruth called this game his greatest thrill.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] At the end of the 1917 season, *Baseball Magazine* rated Bush as the second best shortstop in the American League behind Ray Chapman.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1918, Bush's batting average dropped 47 points from the prior season to .234.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Despite the drop in average, Bush continued to rank among the American League's leaders with 594 plate appearances (1st), 79 bases on balls (2nd), 280 putouts at shortstop (2nd), 74 runs scored (4th), and 48 errors (3rd).
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] *Baseball Magazine* that same year published a feature story on how a player's hands make him suitable for one position or another.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] The author wrote: "Donie Bush is a wonderful shortstop all will agree.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush is a little man perhaps the shortest of stature in organized baseball.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] But his hand is very broad, thick and bony as well as freckled.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1919, Bush continued to perform well defensively.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His 290 assists at shortstop led the American League, and his .943 fielding percentage was third best among the league's shortstops.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Offensively, he continued to rank among the league's leaders with 75 bases on balls (5th), 22 stolen bases (7th), and 82 runs scored (10th).
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1920, Bush led the American League with 48 sacrifice hits—the seventh highest total in Major League history.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Despite his advancing age, Bush retained considerable speed, stealing 15 bases and hitting 18 doubles and five triples.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1921, Ty Cobb took over from Hughie Jennings as manager of the Tigers.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush became involved in repeated arguments with Cobb's "first lieutenant", Dan Howley.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Often Donie becomes so enraged that he pulls his cap off his head and throwing it off the door of the hotel lobby or in the turf of the ball field, stamps on it in his hysteria." For the first half of the season, Bush continued as the Tigers' starting shortstop.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Halfway through the season, however, Cobb moved Bush from his regular shortstop position to second base.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In August 1921, Detroit owner Frank Navin placed Bush on waivers, ending his 13-year career with the Tigers.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In late August 1921, Bush was selected off waivers by the Washington Senators and became the team's starting shortstop for the final 33 games of the 1921 season.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In January 1922, the Senators acquired shortstop Roger Peckinpaugh, relegating Bush to playing second and third base.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush began the 1922 season on a hot streak at the plate.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] By mid-May, he was averaging a run every three at bats, a rate on par with Babe Ruth, leading *The Sporting News* to write that Bush was playing the best baseball of his life.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush appeared in 41 games for the 1922 Senators and finished the season with a .342 on-base percentage and 21 bases on balls in 158 plate appearances.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Despite having a line-up that included Baseball Hall of Famers Walter Johnson, Goose Goslin, Sam Rice, and Bucky Harris, the 1922 Senators finished the season with a 69–85 record and in sixth place in the American League.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In December 1922, Washington owner Clark Griffith hired Bush to replace Clyde Milan as player-manager for the 1923 season.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] *The Sporting News* opined that Bush had the characteristics to make a solid manager: "The same traits that made our friend Donie a great little ball player have been recognized when Clark Griffith appoints him manager.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Brains, a good pair of hands, and a bulldog disposition made him a playing success against the handicap of being undersized and rather weak of arm. . . .
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] On August 2, 1923, Bush noticed early in a game that Hank Severeid and Wally Gerber of the St.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Louis Browns had switched spots in the batting order and batted out of turn.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In the second, fifth and seventh innings both players made outs, and Bush said nothing.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In the ninth inning, Gerber hit a single with two out and a runner on first base.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush appealed to the umpire that Gerber had batted out of order.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Gerber was declared out to end the game.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush led the 1923 Senators to a fourth-place finish and a 75–78 record, two positions higher in the standings and seven fewer losses than the 1922 team.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In October 1923, and despite the improved record, team owner Clark Griffith fired Bush as the team's manager.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] The shift drew criticism from the Washington press, and one newspaper even urged a boycott of the Senators over the firing of Bush.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] After being released by the Senators, Bush returned to his hometown where he was hired as the manager of the Indianapolis Indians of the American Association.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In July 1924, a "Bush Day" was held in Indianapolis with 10,000 fans showing up to honor Bush and present him with gifts.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In his first year as manager of the Indians, Bush led the Indians to a second-place finish in the American Association, narrowly losing the pennant to St.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Paul in the final series of the 1924 season.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] His team again finished in second place in 1925, losing the pennant to Louisville.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1926, Bush developed appendicitis during a road trip and returned to Indianapolis to undergo surgery.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] After a period of convalescence, Bush returned to his role as manager and led the Indians to their third consecutive second-place finish.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In October 1926, Bush was hired to replace Bill McKechnie as manager of the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] The Pirates were loaded with talent but had finished in third place in 1926.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In Bush's first year in Pittsburgh, he led the 1927 Pirates to a National League pennant with a 94–60 record.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] The Pirates were then swept by the soon-to-be famous New York Yankees in the World Series.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] During that season, Bush had a feud with Pirates star Kiki Cuyler.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Cuyler was unhappy about being switched from third to second in the batting order, and he allegedly slackened his effort for a few games.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush reacted by benching Cuyler in August and not playing him again for the rest of the season (using him sparingly for pinch hitting), even keeping him out of the World Series.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush ignored chants from Pirate fans, "We want Cuyler!
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] We want Cuyler", in the games at Pittsburgh.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] After the season, the Pirates traded the future hall of famer in Cuyler to the Cubs.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Cuyler would make it to the World Series once more in his career while the Pirates would not contend again until 1960.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush's Pirates finished in fourth place in 1928 and in second place in 1929.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] During the 1929 season, Bush complained to a Pittsburgh reporter about the new "lively ball", saying, "It's not a ball‚ it's a bullet.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Somebody's going to get killed if they don't watch out.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] A pitcher who has to put the ball over hasn't a chance.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] All he can do is to pitch and duck." (Bush's statement would prove incorrect, as no player has died on the field since Ray Chapman in 1920).
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] At the end of August 1929, Bush suddenly resigned as the Pirates' manager.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] At the time, *The Sporting News* noted that many of the Pittsburgh fans turned against Bush when he benched Cuyler in 1927 and that Bush had never been able to get the local fans behind him.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] On September 30, 1929, Bush signed a two-year contract to serve as the manager of the Chicago White Sox starting with the 1930 season.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He took over a team that had finished in seventh place with a 59–93 record in 1929.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1930, the White Sox again finished in seventh place, improving only slightly to 64–90.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] By July 1931, a public debate was under way as to whether Bush or team owner Charles Comiskey was to blame for the White Sox' poor showing.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Many in the press blamed Comiskey for the shortage of talent at Bush's command.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush resigned at the end of the 1931 season.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1932, Bush managed the Minneapolis Millers in the American Association to a 100–68 record and a first-place finish.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] On November 10, 1932, the Cincinnati Reds announced that they had two weeks earlier retained Bush as manager for the 1933 season.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Upon his hiring, one newspaper reporter predicted: "No bed of roses awaits the new manager here. . . .
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He falls heir to a run-down team, with little financial backing and a quick-to-criticize public." The 1933 Reds finished in last place with a 58–94 record, compiled the lowest batting average (.246) in the National League, and lacked a pitcher who was able to muster more than 10 wins.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In December 1933, Bush was hired as the manager of the Minneapolis Millers, the team he had coached in 1932.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He remained with the Millers from 1934 to 1938 and won pennants in 1934 and 1935.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Ted Williams played for the Millers in 1938, saw his batting average jump 75 points over the prior year, and later credited Bush with some of his success.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In September 1938, Bush announced that he was resigning his position as manager of the Minneapolis Millers to become a co-owner, general manager and field manager of the Louisville Colonels of the American Association.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush and two partners, Indiana banker Frank E.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] McKinney and Tom Yawkey (owner of the Boston Red Sox), purchased the club reportedly for $175,000 -- $100,000 for the plant (including a 14,500-seat park built in 1923 for $400,000) and $75,000 for the franchise and players.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Co-owner Yawkey reportedly objected to the trade, but Bush and McKinney held a majority interest in the club.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] After the 1940 season, Bush and McKinney sold their two-thirds interest to Yawkey.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Louis hospital at the time and stated that he was selling his interest in the team due to poor health.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush remained a resident of Indianapolis throughout his life.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He lived on the 200 block of North Walcott Street in east Indianapolis from at least 1910 through 1940.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In December 1941, after Bush recuperated from a lengthy illness, Bush and McKinney bought the Indianapolis Indians from Norman Perry.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush and McKinney hired Gabby Hartnett as the team's field manager for 1942.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In November 1942, Bush announced that he would take over as field manager in 1943 while continuing as the club's president as well.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush managed the team for the entire 1943 but was forced by ill health to give up his role as field manager in May 1944, hiring his long-time friend Mike Kelly to take over as the team's manager.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] On July 20, 1951, Bush and McKinney sold majority control of the Indianapolis baseball club to the Cleveland Indians.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] On February 25, 1952, Bush was replaced as the club's president after holding the position for nearly 10 years.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush continued to hold a minority interest in the club and remained with the club as an executive without title.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] *The Sporting News* noted that the reorganization marked the first time since Bush's playing days that he had been without an official title.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In November 1952, Bush and McKinney sold their remaining 25% interest in the Indianapolis club to the Cleveland Indians.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] For three years following his disassociation with the Indianapolis club, Bush worked as a scout for the Boston Red Sox.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In January 1956, Bush and McKinney led a successful effort to transform the Indianapolis club into a community-owned team through a public stock offering.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] On January 30, 1956, Bush was named president and general manager of the club.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] On February 1, 1969, Bush announced that he was resigning as the club's president after holding the position continuously since 1956.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush, who was 81 years old, stated that he was quitting as the result of "a front-office squabble" with the club's chairman, Louis Hensley, and general manager, Max Schumacher.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush remained affiliated with professional baseball for 65 years.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1967, the stadium in which the Indianapolis Indians played was renamed from Victory Field to Bush Stadium in his honor.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] In 1972, at age 84, Bush was working as a scout for the Chicago White Sox.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] He fell ill during spring training in Florida and died three weeks later after returning home to Indianapolis.
[src:donie-bush/donie-bush] Bush was posthumously elected to the Indiana Baseball Hall of Fame in 1979 and was known as "Mr.
